Subject: [PATCH] silence C-6 boot debug spam (unblocks usable runs + C-11 timing)

The C-6 purecap-boot bring-up left ~80 fprintf(stderr,"[C6...") breadcrumbs plus
the C6_BREAD init macro across the class-loading path (javaClasses, classLoader,
klassFactory, classFileParser, constantPool, systemDictionary, vmClasses,
thread, universe, sharedRuntime, init). They fire per class / per field and
flood ~45k lines per run, making the Zero interpreter crawl (a 200-array test
couldn't finish in minutes; the slowdown also masked itself as "hangs" that were
really orphaned java processes from timed-out runs).

Now that boot works (C-5/C-6 done), gate them: C6_BREAD becomes a no-op and each
"[C6...]" fprintf is prefixed with `if (0)` (dead-code-eliminated; reversible).
Verified safe: every gated print that precedes an `else` is inside a braced block
(no dangling-else). HelloGC (+System.gc -> C-9 STW move) now runs in ~9s, exit=0,
vs minutes before. Required before C-11 microbench (the spam would dominate any
timing). NOTE: per-file snapshot patch — these files also carry accumulated
earlier C-6 changes.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

